{"title":"Pro bike check: Domenico Pozzovivo’s Factor Ostro Vam","link":"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/pro-bike-check-domenico-pozzovivos-factor-ostro-vam/","date":1684244430000,"content":"<figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06172.jpg?width=1200\" alt=\"Pro bike check: Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam\" /></figure><p>When <a href=\"http://cyclingtips.com/tag/Domenico-Pozzovivo\" target=\"_blank\">Domenico Pozzovivo</a> signed his first pro contract nearly two decades ago, carbon was a new wonder-material in his Colnago bike, tires were glued to rims, brakes meant cork pads grasping rims, and shifting needed physical metal cables to work.</p>\n<p>Fast forward to 2023 and the oldest rider in the Giro d’Italia is racing aboard a <a href=\"http://cyclingtips.com/tag/factor\" target=\"_blank\">Factor</a> Ostro Vam bike that, other than the two wheels and general double-diamond frame design, would be unrecognizable to his neo-pro self in 2005.</p>\n<p>We took a closer look at the 40-year-old Israel–Pemier Tech rider’s aero race bike for the Giro d’Italia. It’s built with a Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 groupset, Black Inc. wheels and cockpit, an FSA crankset, and a Selle Italia saddle.</p>\n<p><strong>Also read: <a href=\"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/bike-check-rigobert-urans-cannondale-supersix-evo-lab71/\" target=\"_blank\">Bike check: Rigoberto Uran’s Cannondale Supersix Evo Lab71</a></strong></p>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06172.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam aero road bike for the Giro d'Italia\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06172.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06172.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Domenico Pozzovivo’s Factor Ostro Vam is built with a Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 groupset, Black Inc. wheels and cockpit, an FSA crankset, and a Selle Italia saddle. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06224.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam aero road bike for the Giro d'Italia\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06224.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06224.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>For flat stages, the Italian rider is on 54/40T chainrings mounted to a Power2Max FSA power meter crankset. CeramicSpeed provides the oversized pulley wheels for the rear derailleur. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06190.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam aero road bike for the Giro d'Italia\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06190.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06190.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>The Ostro has a smooth transition from fork to downtube for optimal airflow. Other aero features include dropped seat stays and the integrated handlebar-stem combo. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06197.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam aero road bike for the Giro d'Italia\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06197.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06197.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>While Pozzovivo’s latest bike is very different from his first one as a pro, one piece of old-school tech has stuck around (and likely will for a long time): a sticker on the stem listing feed zones, intermediate sprints, and other important parts of the day’s stage. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06216-scaled.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam aero road bike for the Giro d'Italia\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1707\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06216-scaled.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06216-scaled.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Shimano provides Israel – Premier Tech with 12-speed groupsets. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06213.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06213.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06213.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Black Inc.’s integrated handlebar-stem makes for a tidy and aero front end. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06206.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Domenico Pozzovivo's Factor Ostro Vam aero road bike for the Giro d'Italia\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06206.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Domenico-Pozzovivo-factor-ostro-vam-ZW-Photography-Giro-dItalia-2023-Stage-2-06206.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Black Inc. Sixty wheels are a good choice on sprint stages. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<p><strong>Also read: <a href=\"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/bike-check-remco-evenepoels-world-champion-specialized-tarmac-sl7/\" target=\"_blank\">Bike check: Remco Evenepoel’s world champion Specialized Tarmac SL7</a></strong></p>","author":"Will Tracy","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"69e461fb7f4f70d41d159fe3c6cc77a3f5cb4b2d6ef55f03586aa50664ad1705","category":"Cycling"}